  "prompt": "Why do case studies have high ecological validity?",
  "response": "Case studies often have high ecological validity because they:\n\n1. Examine real-world settings\n- Study participants in their natural environment\n- Capture authentic behaviors and experiences\n- Reflect realistic conditions and contexts\n\n2. Provide detailed, contextual information\n- Offer comprehensive insights into complex situations\n- Include rich, nuanced data about participants\n- Consider multiple factors influencing behavior\n\n3. Focus on real-life scenarios\n- Investigate actual experiences rather than artificial laboratory conditions\n- Minimize experimental constraints\n- Represent genuine human experiences\n\n4. Allow for in-depth exploration\n- Enable thorough examination of specific situations\n- Capture complex interactions and dynamics\n- Provide holistic understanding of phenomena\n\n5. Minimize experimental manipulation\n- Observe participants in their natural state\n- Reduce artificial research constraints\n- Reflect genuine behavioral patterns\n\n6. Capture individual variations\n- Demonstrate unique personal experiences\n- Highlight individual differences\n- Show how context influences behavior\n\n7. Represent naturalistic conditions\n- Closely mirror real-world circumstances\n- Minimize artificial research environments\n- Provide realistic representations of human experiences\n\nThese characteristics contribute to case studies' high ecological validity by ensuring research closely reflects genuine, everyday environments and experiences.",
